WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.000
[Unknown]: IVM.

00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:03.840
[Amit Varma]: But this is a real India and things are getting worse.

00:01:07.520 --> 00:01:11.840
[Unknown]: Welcome to the scene and the unseen our weekly podcast on economics,

00:01:11.840 --> 00:01:16.080
[Unknown]: politics and behavioral science. Please welcome your host, Amit Badma.

00:01:18.720 --> 00:01:24.320
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to the scene in the unseen. Today's episode is about the impending jobs crisis in India,

00:01:24.320 --> 00:01:29.600
[Amit Varma]: or rather the ongoing jobs crisis. And my guest is my old friend, the brilliant Yaza Chal.

00:01:29.600 --> 00:01:35.520
[Amit Varma]: I first met Yaza around 15 years ago when he was an early blogger like me and used to work as CEO

00:01:35.520 --> 00:01:41.200
[Amit Varma]: of Praja, a Mumbai NGO that works with government to make it more accountable. He then went to the

00:01:41.200 --> 00:01:47.840
[Amit Varma]: US, got an MBA at Yale, worked as a consultant at firms like McKinsey and IBM, and then decided to

00:01:47.840 --> 00:01:53.280
[Amit Varma]: come back to India. He now works at the Takshashila Institution in Bangalore and heads a project

00:01:53.280 --> 00:02:00.080
[Amit Varma]: called 20 million jobs. The purpose of this project is to try and understand India's jobs crisis,

00:02:00.080 --> 00:02:05.120
[Amit Varma]: to propose solutions and bring all of this into the public discourse. There'll be a book at the

00:02:05.120 --> 00:02:10.560
[Amit Varma]: end of this, perhaps even films and so on. But that's down the line. As of now, Yaza and his

00:02:10.560 --> 00:02:15.600
[Amit Varma]: team is collecting data and coming to terms with the enormity of the problem. I've been looking

00:02:15.600 --> 00:02:22.720
[Amit Varma]: forward to this conversation. But before we begin a quick commercial break. Like me, are you someone

00:02:22.720 --> 00:02:27.280
[Amit Varma]: who loves fine art, but can't really afford to have paintings by the artists you like hanging

00:02:27.280 --> 00:02:32.800
[Amit Varma]: on your walls? Well, worry no more. Head on over to Indian colors.com. Indian colors is a company

00:02:32.800 --> 00:02:38.320
[Amit Varma]: that licenses images of the finest modern art from some of the best artists in India and adapts them

00:02:38.320 --> 00:02:44.240
[Amit Varma]: into objects of everyday use. These include wearable art like stoles and shrugs, home decor

00:02:44.240 --> 00:02:48.960
[Amit Varma]: like cushion covers and table runners and accessories like tote bags. This allows art lovers

00:02:48.960 --> 00:02:54.160
[Amit Varma]: to actually get fine art into their homes at an accessible price. And artists get royalties on

00:02:54.160 --> 00:02:59.360
[Amit Varma]: sales just like authors do. What's more, Indian colors now has an exciting range of new products,

00:02:59.360 --> 00:03:04.880
[Amit Varma]: including fridge magnets with some stunning motifs and salad bowls and platters made of mango wood.

00:03:04.880 --> 00:03:10.160
[Amit Varma]: Their artists include luminaries like Babu Xavier, Vazvo x Vazvo, Brinda Miller, Dilip Sharma,

00:03:10.160 --> 00:03:14.880
[Amit Varma]: Shruti Nelson and Pradeep Mishra. They accept bulk orders for corporate and festival gifting.

00:03:14.880 --> 00:03:19.920
[Amit Varma]: But even if you want to buy just for yourself or a friend, head on over to Indian colors.com.

00:03:19.920 --> 00:03:25.520
[Amit Varma]: That's colors with an OU. And if you want a 20% discount, apply the code IBM 20. That's

00:03:25.520 --> 00:03:31.200
[Amit Varma]: IBM for IBM podcast IBM 20 for a 20% discount at Indian colors.com.

00:03:32.080 --> 00:03:33.760
[Amit Varma]: Yazad, welcome to the scene in the unseen.

00:03:34.400 --> 00:03:35.840
[Amit Varma]: Hi, Amit. Thanks for having me.

00:03:36.400 --> 00:03:40.720
[Amit Varma]: Yazad, I've actually done an episode in the past on the jobs crisis. I think it was with Vivek

00:03:40.720 --> 00:03:46.640
[Amit Varma]: Kaul. But I get the sense that even I don't fully understand how bad things are. So so give us all a

00:03:46.640 --> 00:03:49.920
[Amit Varma]: sense of what this jobs crisis is like. How bad is it?

00:03:50.480 --> 00:03:56.800
[Guest]: Okay, it's enormous, is perhaps the best word to put it. According to labor ministry data,

00:03:57.360 --> 00:04:01.440
[Guest]: we have 12 million people entering the workforce every year.

00:04:01.440 --> 00:04:02.800
[Guest]: That's 1 million a month.

00:04:02.800 --> 00:04:09.920
[Guest]: That's right. Additionally, we have approximately six and a half to 7 million jobs that are being

00:04:09.920 --> 00:04:12.400
[Guest]: lost in agriculture every year.

00:04:12.400 --> 00:04:12.960
[Guest]: Wow.

00:04:12.960 --> 00:04:18.960
[Guest]: So we have around about 18 to 19 million jobs that doesn't count other sectors and other job

00:04:18.960 --> 00:04:26.160
[Guest]: losses. So rounding it off, we have around about 20 million jobs that need to be created every year

00:04:26.160 --> 00:04:27.120
[Amit Varma]: in India.

00:04:27.120 --> 00:04:32.000
[Amit Varma]: That's about 16 or 17 lakh people coming into the workforce every month.

00:04:32.000 --> 00:04:39.280
[Guest]: That's right. That's right. So when we look at that, we'd also somebody would ask, but of course,

00:04:39.280 --> 00:04:43.360
[Guest]: jobs are also being created. It's not that you know, we just have this gap.

00:04:44.880 --> 00:04:52.880
[Guest]: Different surveys give us different figures. For example, between 2011 to 2015, we created around

00:04:52.880 --> 00:05:02.080
[Guest]: about 7 million jobs total. Between 2013 and 16, we created between 1.5 to 1.4 million jobs.

00:05:02.080 --> 00:05:06.000
[Guest]: That's one and a half to 4 lakh jobs in the entire year.

00:05:06.800 --> 00:05:07.120
[Guest]: Wow.

00:05:07.120 --> 00:05:10.480
[Guest]: So other surveys show that we create 7 million jobs a year.

00:05:11.200 --> 00:05:17.040
[Guest]: Even the most optimistic of those, which I don't believe talked about by Sujit Bhalla,

00:05:17.040 --> 00:05:24.080
[Guest]: said that we created 12 million jobs in a year. None of those come close to the figure that we

00:05:24.080 --> 00:05:28.400
[Guest]: really need to create the 20 million jobs that we're talking about.

00:05:28.400 --> 00:05:33.360
[Amit Varma]: And frankly, Sujit Bhalla's 12 million figure is just nonsense. He's kind of I mean, I don't want

00:05:33.360 --> 00:05:37.520
[Amit Varma]: to be harsh and focus on personalities, but he's renowned for getting everything wrong through his

00:05:37.520 --> 00:05:38.880
[Amit Varma]: career. So let's not even.

00:05:38.880 --> 00:05:43.760
[Guest]: Yeah, I mean, for example, I'll give you one example where those figures don't work out.

00:05:43.760 --> 00:05:48.800
[Guest]: They take the employment, the EPA for data, the Employment Provident Fund Organization data,

00:05:48.800 --> 00:05:54.560
[Guest]: and then they look at new Provident Fund accounts that have been open for workers aged 18 to 21

00:05:54.560 --> 00:05:59.760
[Guest]: years. And they assume that 80% of workers in this age bracket are first time workers.

00:05:59.760 --> 00:06:05.840
[Guest]: That assumption is not justified. So you arrive at a figure of 1.8 million new jobs in the sector

00:06:05.840 --> 00:06:12.160
[Guest]: and this age group without having any sort of firm foundation for that by just making

00:06:12.960 --> 00:06:16.640
[Guest]: a little bit of statistical, you know, jugaad, if one must say.

00:06:17.840 --> 00:06:25.440
[Guest]: So but the most optimistic of it is even is around about 60% of what is required in the economy

00:06:25.440 --> 00:06:31.040
[Guest]: today. That's the reason why when you have these things like the Railway Recruitment Board or the

00:06:31.040 --> 00:06:40.080
[Guest]: UP police, which, you know, notified for like a few thousand jobs, and they got inside 62 jobs,

00:06:40.080 --> 00:06:46.720
[Guest]: I'm sorry, the UP police gave an ad out for 62 jobs for a communications post, which required

00:06:46.720 --> 00:06:52.720
[Guest]: a fifth standard education. They got more than 3000 PhDs applying for that same job.

00:06:52.720 --> 00:07:00.080
[Guest]: My God. So we have this gap. And that is why you have people who are highly educated,

00:07:00.080 --> 00:07:05.920
[Guest]: looking for the first possible or any possible chance or opportunity they have.

00:07:06.640 --> 00:07:12.240
[Guest]: So in a sense, the situation is quite dire. And that, you know, that speaks to a number

00:07:12.240 --> 00:07:17.440
[Amit Varma]: of things like that kind of a figure with 1000s and even lakhs of, you know, where you have more

00:07:17.440 --> 00:07:21.120
[Amit Varma]: than 300 applicants for a single low level government job. And so many people are so

00:07:21.120 --> 00:07:24.880
[Amit Varma]: well educated speaks to a number of things. One, it tells you that there's just a lack of jobs out

00:07:24.880 --> 00:07:31.520
[Amit Varma]: there. Two, it tells you that there's a mismatch between education and employment that somehow that

00:07:31.520 --> 00:07:37.120
[Amit Varma]: demand supply relationship that should exist between the two does not and obviously, we've

00:07:37.120 --> 00:07:40.960
[Amit Varma]: both spoken about this many times in the past part of this is because markets aren't allowed

00:07:40.960 --> 00:07:47.200
[Amit Varma]: to operate in either of those fields. And that causes a mismatch. And also, there is an

00:07:47.200 --> 00:07:54.000
[Amit Varma]: interesting point that these people that there is this greater demand for public sector jobs,

00:07:54.000 --> 00:07:59.200
[Amit Varma]: government jobs, because that just not only tells you that that kind of security is valued,

00:07:59.200 --> 00:08:05.840
[Amit Varma]: but it also tells you the uncertainty and the insecurities that come with private sector jobs

00:08:05.840 --> 00:08:10.880
[Amit Varma]: and private sector jobs across India aren't really the sort of jobs that elites like you and I might

00:08:10.880 --> 00:08:15.360
[Amit Varma]: get where you get a salary and you have your perquisites and all and there's a contract and

00:08:15.360 --> 00:08:20.800
[Amit Varma]: all of that. But they're pretty dire. Most of them are in the informal sector, which only exists

00:08:20.800 --> 00:08:26.960
[Amit Varma]: because of bad regulation. But I'll come to all of these later. I'd like to explore all of these.

00:08:26.960 --> 00:08:32.400
[Amit Varma]: But first, just sort of start with a basic point of misunderstanding that a lot of people have. Can

00:08:32.400 --> 00:08:37.040
[Guest]: you define what a job is for me? So that's that's actually difficult to do. So whether it's paid

00:08:37.040 --> 00:08:44.000
[Guest]: employment or self employment, there is no clear definition of a job. What we do have is we have

00:08:44.000 --> 00:08:50.800
[Guest]: formal jobs and informal jobs in India. So a formal job has an explicit contract. Okay,

00:08:50.800 --> 00:08:56.640
[Guest]: while an informal job has no such contract to it. And additionally, we have what we call the

00:08:56.640 --> 00:09:03.440
[Guest]: organized sector and the unorganized sector. So the unorganized sector is basically unincorporated

00:09:03.440 --> 00:09:09.120
[Guest]: private enterprises with 10 or less workers in them. Right. So these are the micro and the mini

00:09:09.120 --> 00:09:15.760
[Guest]: kind of organizations. And between 80 to 90% of working age population people either work in this

00:09:15.760 --> 00:09:21.840
[Guest]: unorganized sector. So a large percentage of these are self employed. And part of this unorganized

00:09:21.840 --> 00:09:29.040
[Amit Varma]: sector might be formal or is all of it informal? Part of it could be formal, but very doubtful. So

00:09:29.040 --> 00:09:34.960
[Guest]: most of it the formal sector is in the formal organized sector, right, is what we really focus

00:09:34.960 --> 00:09:42.400
[Guest]: on. So when for example, there was a news item recently that we had tech firms were hiring. So

00:09:42.400 --> 00:09:47.520
[Guest]: those would all be formal jobs in the organized sector. These are large companies like TCS and

00:09:47.520 --> 00:09:52.960
[Guest]: Wipro and Infosys that were hiring. And a big hoo-ha was made about it. But the total number

00:09:52.960 --> 00:09:59.920
[Guest]: of jobs if I remember right was around about 24,000. Right. So and there was there was supposed

00:09:59.920 --> 00:10:06.000
[Guest]: to be big news that 24,000 jobs new jobs being created. So those would all be formal organized

00:10:06.000 --> 00:10:11.200
[Guest]: sector jobs. But the vast majority of people who work in this country work in the informal and the

00:10:11.200 --> 00:10:16.320
[Amit Varma]: unorganized sector. So I'll take a brief detour here. What is the informal or unorganized sector?

00:10:16.320 --> 00:10:23.120
[Guest]: Why does it exist? It exists because most small organizations in the country haven't been able

00:10:23.120 --> 00:10:33.120
[Guest]: to scale up for a variety of reasons. And also because in this because of labor laws, it makes

00:10:33.120 --> 00:10:39.760
[Guest]: sense, you know, to kind of keep your organization small. So those are roughly the two reasons why

00:10:39.760 --> 00:10:44.000
[Guest]: you'd have a large number of organized unorganized sector workers in the country.

00:10:44.000 --> 00:10:48.080
[Amit Varma]: In fact, I had a rant on this a couple of episodes ago, I think the demonetization episode

00:10:48.080 --> 00:10:54.080
[Amit Varma]: with our mutual friend Shruti, where we were lamenting how, you know, the informal sector is

00:10:54.080 --> 00:10:58.240
[Amit Varma]: often treated as if there is something morally wrong in being informal, you're evading taxes or

00:10:58.240 --> 00:11:03.360
[Amit Varma]: whatever. And what people don't understand and what I want to just keep stressing is that the

00:11:03.360 --> 00:11:09.040
[Amit Varma]: reason the informal sector exists is because it is forced to because government regulations are

00:11:09.040 --> 00:11:14.160
[Amit Varma]: so draconian and so stringent that most of those companies would not be able to comply and would

00:11:14.160 --> 00:11:20.080
[Amit Varma]: not be able to exist in the formal sector. And therefore, they are forced to exist in the informal

00:11:20.080 --> 00:11:27.040
[Amit Varma]: sector. And that prevents them from scaling up to the kind of level that they otherwise would,

00:11:27.040 --> 00:11:32.320
[Amit Varma]: which would be great for both the nation and the economy in this whole virtuous cycle positive

00:11:32.320 --> 00:11:38.320
[Amit Varma]: some kind of way where they would generate far more employment, and so on. So we should not look

00:11:38.320 --> 00:11:43.760
[Amit Varma]: at the informal sector as people who are somehow outside the law, but as people who are not

00:11:43.760 --> 00:11:48.240
[Amit Varma]: allowed to function because of the draconian nature of the law.

00:11:48.240 --> 00:11:54.960
[Guest]: That's true. Sometime back, we were talking to an exporter of textiles, garment manufacturer and

00:11:54.960 --> 00:12:00.800
[Guest]: exporter, a quite large conglomerate. And they were telling me that they keep their factories

00:12:00.800 --> 00:12:07.200
[Guest]: to round about two and a half thousand workers max, because of infrastructure reasons as well.

00:12:07.200 --> 00:12:12.240
[Guest]: They want to make sure the workers you know, are able to come to the factory easily enough,

00:12:12.240 --> 00:12:17.520
[Guest]: while in villages and other areas, it's if it's more than an hour's journey,

00:12:18.560 --> 00:12:22.320
[Guest]: people simply won't come to work. And that infrastructure doesn't exist

00:12:22.320 --> 00:12:26.160
[Guest]: in rural areas to help people simply commute to work.

00:12:26.160 --> 00:12:30.240
[Amit Varma]: Right. And the other interesting thing, and this will lead me to my next question. And the other

00:12:30.240 --> 00:12:35.760
[Amit Varma]: interesting thing here is that you mentioned how there was so much hoo-ha and hype about the 24,000

00:12:35.760 --> 00:12:42.320
[Amit Varma]: new jobs, which were all created in the formal sector, and again, for relative elites. And what

00:12:42.320 --> 00:12:47.200
[Amit Varma]: people don't understand often is that much of the data is either coming from the much of the data

00:12:47.200 --> 00:12:52.320
[Amit Varma]: on jobs is either coming from the formal sector, or it's extrapolations from data that comes from

00:12:52.320 --> 00:12:57.600
[Amit Varma]: the formal sector. The informal sector is very hard to get data that, you know, labor contractors

00:12:57.600 --> 00:13:01.680
[Amit Varma]: kitne hain, pakore wala kitna hain and so on. Which is why when you look at something like

00:13:01.680 --> 00:13:08.240
[Amit Varma]: demonetization, for example, it's hard to estimate the damage it did, because most of the damage

00:13:08.240 --> 00:13:13.200
[Amit Varma]: would have happened in the informal sector, which runs mainly on cash. And, of course, 86% of the

00:13:13.200 --> 00:13:19.040
[Amit Varma]: cash supply was cut off. And you have no idea of how many companies shut down in the margins,

00:13:19.040 --> 00:13:23.360
[Amit Varma]: how many livelihoods were destroyed, because none of that is reflected in the data is that

00:13:23.360 --> 00:13:27.840
[Amit Varma]: sort of accurate. And then the next broader question, which I'd like you to sort of expound

00:13:27.840 --> 00:13:32.080
[Amit Varma]: on is, what are the problems you face when you're doing a sort of project like this,

00:13:32.080 --> 00:13:34.880
[Amit Varma]: where you're trying to understand the jobs crisis with data?

00:13:35.520 --> 00:13:40.320
[Guest]: So there's a lot of problems with data. I mean, the Prime Minister himself has talked about

00:13:40.320 --> 00:13:45.040
[Guest]: and confessed that, you know, regarding data, there's hardly any numbers available in employment

00:13:45.040 --> 00:13:51.200
[Guest]: statistics, he tried to get out of giving figures for this. But he's right in the sense that we

00:13:51.200 --> 00:13:56.480
[Guest]: have data from different sources. We have Labor Ministry data, we have the NSSO data,

00:13:56.480 --> 00:14:01.520
[Guest]: the National Sample Survey Organization data, we have data from sources like the Employees

00:14:01.520 --> 00:14:07.360
[Guest]: Provident Fund, which we shouldn't really be using for job markets data. But there is no

00:14:07.920 --> 00:14:14.640
[Guest]: central statistical kind of data repository. And apart from that, there is no consistent

00:14:14.640 --> 00:14:22.560
[Guest]: collection of data as well. So very often, one has to rely on private sector data, data from sources

00:14:22.560 --> 00:14:29.040
[Guest]: like the CMI, the Center for Monitoring the Indian Economy, and different sources of data then give

00:14:29.040 --> 00:14:36.160
[Guest]: different pictures. And one is confused at times at which source to take what kind of assumptions

00:14:36.160 --> 00:14:41.840
[Guest]: to make, how does one reconcile the data from different sources, it's something that we are

00:14:41.840 --> 00:14:46.880
[Guest]: still grappling with right now, looking at all these figures and trying to make sense of them

00:14:47.520 --> 00:14:52.480
[Guest]: is a huge part of the problem as well. And that's one reason why we haven't been able to estimate

00:14:52.480 --> 00:14:58.240
[Guest]: for example, how many jobs the economy is creating. So let's say you have certain data sets

00:14:58.240 --> 00:15:04.000
[Amit Varma]: at your disposal, and you make of them what you do. But beyond that, what are the sort of broad

00:15:04.000 --> 00:15:09.680
[Amit Varma]: metrics that you draw upon to kind of figure out how bad the problem is, is the problem getting

00:15:09.680 --> 00:15:16.000
[Amit Varma]: worse. And also there is, you know, this added element of the fact that India is getting younger.

00:15:16.000 --> 00:15:20.880
[Amit Varma]: And this was supposed to be what people call the demographic dividend. Because you know,

00:15:20.880 --> 00:15:26.480
[Amit Varma]: the average age in the country today is 27 60% of the country is actually born after liberalization,

00:15:26.480 --> 00:15:31.520
[Amit Varma]: so they can't possibly relate to what we went through before that. And which is why there's

00:15:31.520 --> 00:15:38.160
[Amit Varma]: also a sort of growing romanticization among young people of socialist ideas, and so on,

00:15:38.160 --> 00:15:41.920
[Amit Varma]: because they haven't lived through those years. But that's an aside. But leaving that aside,

00:15:42.640 --> 00:15:48.160
[Amit Varma]: you know, we were supposed to benefit from this demographic dividend, where these 10s of millions

00:15:48.160 --> 00:15:55.360
[Amit Varma]: of enthusiastic entrepreneurial young people will take the country forward. But what we instead have

00:15:55.360 --> 00:16:00.000
[Amit Varma]: is more of a demographic disaster where you have these 10s of millions of young people coming into

00:16:00.000 --> 00:16:05.200
[Amit Varma]: the workforce as the country gets younger, but they haven't been educated well, which is a whole

00:16:05.200 --> 00:16:11.680
[Amit Varma]: different subject. And even those who have some education are misfits and cannot get the kind of

00:16:11.680 --> 00:16:17.200
[Amit Varma]: jobs that the skill requires or don't have the skills that the jobs require. So what are sort of

00:16:17.200 --> 00:16:22.960
[Amit Varma]: when you try to build a long term narrative of this, what are the different kinds of strands

00:16:22.960 --> 00:16:28.400
[Guest]: that you look at? Sure. So there, I wouldn't be that pessimistic. I think we still have a

00:16:28.400 --> 00:16:34.720
[Guest]: demographic dividend. I'm hoping that it does not turn into a disaster. Although we seem to be going

00:16:34.720 --> 00:16:41.200
[Guest]: that way right now. So for example, one of the things we look at is labor force participation

00:16:41.200 --> 00:16:46.160
[Guest]: rate. So what is the percentage of the population that is actually participating in the labor force?

00:16:46.160 --> 00:16:52.800
[Guest]: And that has seen a decline. So between 2011 and 15, we saw a 3% decline in the labor force

00:16:52.800 --> 00:17:01.760
[Guest]: participation rate from 55% to around about 52%. But what's far more worrying is that the female

00:17:01.760 --> 00:17:09.200
[Guest]: labor force participation rate has declined dramatically from around about 34% to 27%

00:17:09.200 --> 00:17:17.280
[Guest]: in the last two decades. So there are far fewer women working. And this is especially true in the

00:17:17.280 --> 00:17:24.320
[Guest]: middle income sector. So you don't see that really in poor women, and you don't see that in highly

00:17:24.320 --> 00:17:29.360
[Guest]: educated women, but you see that in the sector in between, where women are actually dropping out the

00:17:29.360 --> 00:17:36.160
[Guest]: labor force to stay at home. Now, one reason being given is that, you know, if you have higher income

00:17:36.160 --> 00:17:41.760
[Guest]: and the male is able to provide for the family, then, you know, the woman doesn't see any need

00:17:41.760 --> 00:17:48.240
[Guest]: to work. And there are also social kind of strictures or social conditions that, you know,

00:17:48.240 --> 00:17:54.240
[Guest]: create some sort of barrier for women working. But that's a concerning figure. I mean, countries

00:17:54.240 --> 00:18:00.240
[Guest]: like Bangladesh have higher female labor force participation rates that we do, close to 10%

00:18:00.240 --> 00:18:07.440
[Guest]: more than us. Apart from that, what we've seen recently is that jobs in agriculture are falling.

00:18:08.000 --> 00:18:17.440
[Guest]: We've seen 26 million jobs lost in agriculture in the same period 2011-15, while we've seen

00:18:17.440 --> 00:18:24.560
[Guest]: non-farm jobs grow by 33 million. So that's what gives us, we were talking earlier, the 7 million

00:18:24.560 --> 00:18:31.280
[Guest]: figure of jobs being created in those years. So that's one figure we look at the labor force

00:18:31.280 --> 00:18:37.200
[Amit Varma]: participation rate. And just a segue for my listeners, as far as women's labor force participation

00:18:37.200 --> 00:18:42.560
[Amit Varma]: is concerned, Namita Bhandare had an excellent series in India Spend last year. And your

00:18:42.560 --> 00:18:47.040
[Amit Varma]: colleague Devika Kher has written about this on Pragati at thinkpragati.com, the magazine I read.

00:18:47.680 --> 00:18:53.120
[Amit Varma]: So do check those out. And when I first realized this, this was very counterintuitive and mind

00:18:53.120 --> 00:18:59.600
[Amit Varma]: blowing for me because I had always assumed that as India progresses, and as things get better for

00:18:59.600 --> 00:19:04.400
[Amit Varma]: women, for example, I point to a figure like rising divorce rates as a very positive metric for the

00:19:04.400 --> 00:19:09.360
[Amit Varma]: empowerment of women. And my assumption was that however slow it is, women are getting empowered.

00:19:09.360 --> 00:19:15.200
[Amit Varma]: So to then find that the labor force participation has actually declined was a huge revelation for

00:19:15.200 --> 00:19:20.000
[Amit Varma]: me, which I'm still sort of wrapping my head about. And to mention that, for the reasons you

00:19:20.000 --> 00:19:23.680
[Amit Varma]: mentioned, and you know, you can check out the other articles, especially Namita Bhandare's

00:19:23.680 --> 00:19:29.280
[Amit Varma]: analysis for more on that. And the interesting thing about the job loss in agriculture and is

00:19:29.280 --> 00:19:33.840
[Amit Varma]: also that that is not necessarily a bad thing. You know, you and I have been arguing forever that,

00:19:33.840 --> 00:19:38.960
[Amit Varma]: you know, around 50 to 60% of this country is employed in agriculture, the relative figure

00:19:38.960 --> 00:19:44.880
[Amit Varma]: there in other countries is 5% or 6% in the US and in Europe. Part of the reason that so much of the

00:19:44.880 --> 00:19:49.040
[Amit Varma]: countries trapped in the cycle of dependencies, again, bad government policy, and they're not able

00:19:49.040 --> 00:19:53.760
[Amit Varma]: to escape. And we've had some episodes on this in the past, including the very last episode with

00:19:53.760 --> 00:19:58.720
[Amit Varma]: Mr. Gunwant Patil in Hindi, please check that out. And one of the ways through which this has

00:19:58.720 --> 00:20:03.360
[Amit Varma]: happened elsewhere across the world at that 50% becomes 5%, which is a natural process everyone

00:20:03.360 --> 00:20:09.840
[Amit Varma]: goes through, is that productivity has gone up in those countries. And it hasn't to the same extent

00:20:09.840 --> 00:20:15.280
[Amit Varma]: here. And I know you have some larger points to make on labor force productivity, not just in the

00:20:15.280 --> 00:20:21.360
[Guest]: agriculture sector, but overall. So yes, labor productivity itself that we're looking at,

00:20:21.360 --> 00:20:27.440
[Guest]: once again, we're looking at these figures, the years 2011 to 15, for which we have proper data

00:20:28.080 --> 00:20:35.520
[Guest]: that fell to 3.84%. So during the first decade of the century from 2000 to 2010,

00:20:36.080 --> 00:20:44.160
[Guest]: our productivity grew at an annual rate of 5.52%. Now, labor force productivity is a very important

00:20:44.160 --> 00:20:46.880
[Guest]: figure when you're looking at GDP,

00:20:46.880 --> 00:20:51.680
[Amit Varma]: Can you define it for me? So I don't know the term. So I'm assuming that labor force productivity is

00:20:51.680 --> 00:20:54.720
[Amit Varma]: you sort of divide the GDP by the number of people in the labor force.

00:20:55.440 --> 00:20:56.000
[Amit Varma]: That's right.

00:20:56.000 --> 00:20:59.120
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, you say that, okay, each person is producing this much value.

00:20:59.120 --> 00:21:01.280
[Guest]: Correct. You defined it.

00:21:01.840 --> 00:21:02.560
[Guest]: Right.

00:21:02.560 --> 00:21:07.760
[Guest]: So now to obtain higher GDP growth, for example, if you have to obtain a GDP growth of 9%,

00:21:07.760 --> 00:21:15.440
[Guest]: we need to see our labor force productivity grow at around about 7.3%. In 2015, it was 4.2%.

00:21:15.440 --> 00:21:21.760
[Guest]: That was how much it grew by in 2015. If you want to see 10% GDP growth, we need to see our labor

00:21:21.760 --> 00:21:27.840
[Guest]: productivity grow at around about 8.3%. So these are important figures. To look at it another way,

00:21:29.520 --> 00:21:35.760
[Guest]: most of the workers that we have are medium skilled workers in India. 60% of workers in India

00:21:35.760 --> 00:21:44.560
[Guest]: are medium skilled. Only 15% are high skilled. And most economies that did make that transition

00:21:44.560 --> 00:21:51.600
[Guest]: from developing to developed, you know, moved into having higher labor force productivity.

00:21:51.600 --> 00:21:56.720
[Guest]: Now today, for example, economies, developed economies, their labor productivity grows

00:21:56.720 --> 00:22:03.040
[Guest]: around about 2 to 3%, but they have a much wider base. So for us to reach that percentage,

00:22:03.040 --> 00:22:09.680
[Guest]: to us to reach that GDP growth, we need our labor productivity to grow at a commensurate rate.

00:22:11.920 --> 00:22:16.080
[Guest]: France, if I'm not wrong, is the country with the highest labor force productivity.

00:22:16.960 --> 00:22:21.680
[Guest]: And their labor is round about 40 times as productive as ours is.

00:22:21.680 --> 00:22:24.480
[Amit Varma]: And part of the point, if I read you correctly, you're making is,

00:22:24.480 --> 00:22:27.200
[Amit Varma]: is a question of the level of skilling in a highly skilled job,

00:22:27.200 --> 00:22:32.880
[Amit Varma]: you end up producing much more of value than say you're doing a lowly skilled job, like if you're

00:22:32.880 --> 00:22:37.680
[Amit Varma]: a worker in a factory whose only job is to put nails into something. And you have a whole bunch

00:22:37.680 --> 00:22:42.800
[Amit Varma]: of manual laborers like that, and that productivity isn't high. So part of the secret, therefore,

00:22:42.800 --> 00:22:49.520
[Amit Varma]: is that you have skilling going up. So, you know, more and more people do sort of more highly

00:22:49.520 --> 00:22:54.400
[Amit Varma]: skilled jobs instead of getting stuck there. And part of the issue is that scale brings productivity.

00:22:54.400 --> 00:22:59.680
[Amit Varma]: And as we just discussed, Indian companies aren't really allowed to scale. And therefore,

00:22:59.680 --> 00:23:03.360
[Amit Varma]: that keeps the productivity low. Even Indian agriculture, as my guest last week pointed out.

00:23:04.560 --> 00:23:09.600
[Guest]: So one reason why you know, you see only 5% of people working in agriculture is because

00:23:09.600 --> 00:23:16.320
[Guest]: you see those 5% are really highly skilled. You're using technologies, you're using

00:23:17.120 --> 00:23:22.720
[Guest]: harvesters, you're using tractors, and so on and so forth. And you have fewer people working on

00:23:22.720 --> 00:23:28.240
[Guest]: much larger tracts of land. While today in India, we have a lot of people working on smaller tracts

00:23:28.240 --> 00:23:34.000
[Guest]: of land. So that's why agricultural productivity isn't high. Even other sectors productivity in

00:23:34.000 --> 00:23:41.200
[Guest]: India needs to rise even in the manufacturing sector, where we've seen productivity stagnate

00:23:41.200 --> 00:23:46.720
[Amit Varma]: by and large. Here people might naturally ask that, okay, 50% of the country approximately

00:23:46.720 --> 00:23:52.240
[Amit Varma]: today survives on agriculture. 60 actually. Yeah. And it's a sort of a nebulous figure,

00:23:52.240 --> 00:23:56.080
[Amit Varma]: because a lot of that is part time. And you know, it's associated. I mean, they're not directly

00:23:56.080 --> 00:24:00.320
[Amit Varma]: farmers, but whatever, leaving aside, it's let's say it's around 50%. And it's much more than it

00:24:00.320 --> 00:24:05.280
[Amit Varma]: should be. But if productivity in agriculture goes up, and that number comes to 5%, what happens to

00:24:05.280 --> 00:24:09.360
[Amit Varma]: the rest of the people? Where do they get employed? How are those jobs being generated?

00:24:09.360 --> 00:24:14.240
[Guest]: That's a really big question, because that would be even more than 20 billion that we'd require.

00:24:14.240 --> 00:24:20.240
[Guest]: Exactly. And what we see is, we do see a lot of disguised unemployment out there where we think

00:24:20.240 --> 00:24:25.680
[Guest]: people are employed, but they're not. And that bubbles up, you know, if it's not kind of taken

00:24:25.680 --> 00:24:30.000
[Amit Varma]: care of, it bubbles up into social and political spheres. Give me an example of that disguised

00:24:30.000 --> 00:24:35.280
[Amit Varma]: unemployment, like where we think they're employed, but they're not. So where, for example, an example

00:24:35.280 --> 00:24:40.080
[Guest]: is that you think that there are five people working on a farm, and that's what's being

00:24:40.080 --> 00:24:44.000
[Guest]: reported, but there are only two people working on the farm. And there are three guys who are just

00:24:44.000 --> 00:24:50.960
[Guest]: sitting around doing nothing. So those three guys are disguised unemployed. We think

00:24:50.960 --> 00:24:54.800
[Guest]: that they're employed, but they're not actually being employed. They're not actually doing any

00:24:54.800 --> 00:25:02.320
[Guest]: work. It's just two people doing that work. And you see that coming out in social unrest in the

00:25:02.320 --> 00:25:08.720
[Guest]: country, whether it be, you know, in these WhatsApp lynchings that happen where people get agitated,

00:25:08.720 --> 00:25:16.000
[Guest]: whether it be in, you know, these cow lynchings that are happening. So all of these bubble up in

00:25:16.000 --> 00:25:21.440
[Guest]: social unrest as well. And it's important to look at the fact that it's not just restricted to

00:25:21.440 --> 00:25:28.000
[Guest]: economics. You'd see these employment issues coming out in a variety of ways if they're not

00:25:28.000 --> 00:25:33.280
[Amit Varma]: handled or dealt with. And our mutual friend, the economist Kumar Anand, he's from Bihar, and

00:25:33.280 --> 00:25:37.680
[Amit Varma]: he had gone to Bihar recently to spend time at Saharsa, which is his hometown, and he came back

00:25:37.680 --> 00:25:41.520
[Amit Varma]: and we were chatting and he traveled through Bihar during that trip. And we came back and he

00:25:41.520 --> 00:25:46.080
[Amit Varma]: was chatting and he said that one of the images which will haunt him forever, and a recurring

00:25:46.080 --> 00:25:51.200
[Amit Varma]: image which he saw not in his nightmares, but in, you know, in real life in actual Bihar, was that

00:25:51.920 --> 00:25:58.160
[Amit Varma]: in so many public spaces, there would just be dozens and dozens of young men, young men just

00:25:58.160 --> 00:26:02.560
[Amit Varma]: standing doing nothing. Maybe they're standing around the pawn shop, maybe they're just standing

00:26:02.560 --> 00:26:06.560
[Amit Varma]: on the street looking at their phones or talking to each other or, you know, smoking cigarettes,

00:26:06.560 --> 00:26:12.400
[Amit Varma]: or they're just standing there. And this was an image I asked Nigdha Poonam about when I did an

00:26:12.400 --> 00:26:16.160
[Amit Varma]: episode on Young India with her. Nigdha Poonam, of course, has written the excellent book Dreamers.

00:26:16.880 --> 00:26:21.440
[Amit Varma]: And she kind of corroborated that she said that that was a familiar sight for her as well.

00:26:21.440 --> 00:26:29.520
[Amit Varma]: And again, one of the things a book does is kind of examine what, what these young men do,

00:26:29.520 --> 00:26:33.520
[Amit Varma]: what they sort of go through the different directions they can go in and she had a very

00:26:33.520 --> 00:26:39.120
[Amit Varma]: powerful chapter on anger, on what they do with their anger. And a lot of these men, like for

00:26:39.120 --> 00:26:44.240
[Amit Varma]: example, she followed a guy who was part of a Gauraksha gang, and it lifted his social status

00:26:44.240 --> 00:26:50.720
[Amit Varma]: to be able to express his bigotry in that way, instead of keeping it suppressed. And you know,

00:26:50.720 --> 00:26:54.160
[Amit Varma]: 20 years ago, it would have been the opposite, you'd benefit from suppressing your bigotry and

00:26:54.160 --> 00:27:01.040
[Amit Varma]: pretending to be a reasonable person. But now, it actually pays to sort of act out on those impulses.

00:27:01.040 --> 00:27:05.760
[Amit Varma]: And there was another person she profiled who was a warrior against Love Jihad, for example.

00:27:05.760 --> 00:27:10.320
[Amit Varma]: And, and it's kind of worrying that when you just spoke about the social cost of all this,

00:27:10.320 --> 00:27:14.560
[Amit Varma]: this guy's unemployment or underemployment, which I shall also ask you about, or just

00:27:14.560 --> 00:27:19.600
[Amit Varma]: flat out unemployment that people are coming into the workforce, they are young and they don't have

00:27:19.600 --> 00:27:23.840
[Amit Varma]: jobs and where do they go and one of the things they do is they become foot soldiers for whatever

00:27:23.840 --> 00:27:31.440
[Amit Varma]: movement appeals to their inherent tribalism. Correct. And, you know, political parties and

00:27:31.440 --> 00:27:38.080
[Guest]: other institutions are taking misusing, you know, a lot of these foot soldiers for their own ends.

00:27:38.880 --> 00:27:44.640
[Guest]: And Siddhartha Poonam has talked about that. There's also this case where, you know, where

00:27:44.640 --> 00:27:51.280
[Guest]: you have farmers whose children who are educated, or somewhat educated, then no longer want to go

00:27:51.280 --> 00:27:59.520
[Guest]: into agriculture, but they don't find any other avenues for them. So they're, they think that

00:27:59.520 --> 00:28:04.240
[Guest]: they've evolved beyond agriculture, they have more aspirational objectives, they want to get to

00:28:04.960 --> 00:28:10.000
[Guest]: a government job, ideally, which they find it very difficult to get. And therefore, they're,

00:28:10.000 --> 00:28:15.920
[Guest]: you know, part of that group of people that you've seen around standing, you know, in village squares,

00:28:15.920 --> 00:28:21.760
[Guest]: doing nothing. And, you know, ready to do the bidding of the first person who comes along and

00:28:21.760 --> 00:28:28.000
[Guest]: says, I'll give you 300 rupees per day, would you go out and do that? You can kind of fill in the

00:28:28.000 --> 00:28:34.480
[Amit Varma]: blanks and what that could be. Right. So and I have a couple of questions and taking on from that.

00:28:34.480 --> 00:28:36.960
[Amit Varma]: I'm going to ask you those after a brief commercial break.

