[Amit Varma]: Institution called 20 million jobs, whose idea is to make sense of the jobs crisis in India.

00:29:53.360 --> 00:29:57.440
[Amit Varma]: And if possible, if there are solutions, he's more positive about it than I am,

00:29:57.440 --> 00:30:03.040
[Amit Varma]: suggest solutions. So Yazad, we were discussing these millions and millions of people coming into

00:30:03.040 --> 00:30:09.280
[Amit Varma]: the workforce on a regular basis, and there are no jobs for them. And there's a very sort of

00:30:09.280 --> 00:30:15.200
[Amit Varma]: interesting anecdote that, like, first of all, I like I have two related observations, one of which

00:30:15.200 --> 00:30:20.320
[Amit Varma]: leads into a question, the first observation about people not wanting to do farming anymore,

00:30:21.120 --> 00:30:24.960
[Amit Varma]: is an observation I've made in the past, I think I had an episode with Vivek Kaur where we spoke

00:30:24.960 --> 00:30:31.360
[Amit Varma]: about this. But and I keep talking about it that all the recent youth agitations we have had in

00:30:31.360 --> 00:30:36.880
[Amit Varma]: the country are not over some higher causes or some great noble principles of fighting for freedom,

00:30:36.880 --> 00:30:41.920
[Amit Varma]: or so on and so forth. But they're all about jobs. And if you notice if all you know, whether it's

00:30:41.920 --> 00:30:49.200
[Amit Varma]: the party that's in Gujarat, or the Jats in Haryana, or the Marathas in Maharashtra, they're

00:30:49.200 --> 00:30:54.080
[Amit Varma]: all from landowning castes. And what's kind of happened there is that with every generation,

00:30:54.080 --> 00:30:59.200
[Amit Varma]: the amount of land that a family has basically gets split among the descendants who are usually

00:30:59.200 --> 00:31:03.280
[Amit Varma]: more than one, and therefore the land grows smaller and smaller. And what has happened with

00:31:03.280 --> 00:31:08.960
[Amit Varma]: this generation, especially, is that land sizes across India of these landowning castes have

00:31:08.960 --> 00:31:14.160
[Amit Varma]: gotten so small that they're simply not sustainable. Now, we've discussed in past episodes on agriculture,

00:31:14.160 --> 00:31:19.120
[Amit Varma]: how you're not even allowed to exit agriculture, you can't sell agricultural land for non agricultural

00:31:19.120 --> 00:31:24.160
[Amit Varma]: purposes. So these young men, even if they wanted to can't make a living of agriculture, there isn't

00:31:24.160 --> 00:31:29.520
[Amit Varma]: enough. And therefore they are agitating for jobs which are not being generated by industry.

00:31:29.520 --> 00:31:35.280
[Amit Varma]: And all of these agitations are for increased reservations and government jobs. And that's a

00:31:35.280 --> 00:31:40.960
[Amit Varma]: really scary trend that all of these recent youth agitations are about jobs, and at some level,

00:31:40.960 --> 00:31:44.880
[Amit Varma]: arising from the failure of our agricultural policy. And my second observation at the end

00:31:44.880 --> 00:31:51.040
[Amit Varma]: of which I have sort of a question for you, which you are uniquely placed to answer is our mutual

00:31:51.040 --> 00:31:58.960
[Amit Varma]: friend, Mohit Satyanand had once told us about how he in Himachal, he lives part of the year in

00:31:58.960 --> 00:32:04.240
[Amit Varma]: Himachal and he's spent a lot of time there. And he had once retired and gone there before he came

00:32:04.240 --> 00:32:11.200
[Amit Varma]: back and now lives in Delhi. And he lives in a village called Satholi. And he's seen these kids

00:32:11.200 --> 00:32:16.240
[Amit Varma]: grow up there over this 20 year period. And he points out that how what often happens there is

00:32:16.240 --> 00:32:23.920
[Amit Varma]: that the children of tradesmen like plumbers and watchmen and so on and so forth, they get a certain

00:32:23.920 --> 00:32:28.880
[Amit Varma]: kind of education in the sense that they do their 10th, they maybe do their 12th also, whether it's

00:32:28.880 --> 00:32:33.360
[Amit Varma]: in government schools or private schools or whatever. And having done that education, they

00:32:33.360 --> 00:32:38.080
[Amit Varma]: then feel entitled to more than what their parents got. They don't want to be plumbers and they don't

00:32:38.080 --> 00:32:42.400
[Amit Varma]: want to be sweepers and they don't want to be chowkidar. So they refuse those kind of jobs.

00:32:42.400 --> 00:32:46.400
[Amit Varma]: But at the same time, they haven't learned those traits either. But at the same time,

00:32:46.960 --> 00:32:51.840
[Amit Varma]: they have been enormously undereducated. So they're not really equipped to do anything else.

00:32:51.840 --> 00:32:56.960
[Amit Varma]: And this brings me to one of the points I made at the start of the episode that there is

00:32:56.960 --> 00:33:02.320
[Amit Varma]: an enormous that part of the jobs crisis comes from our education crisis, that there is a mismatch.

00:33:02.320 --> 00:33:09.680
[Amit Varma]: Our education system is not turning out people who are good for anything. And it is also not

00:33:09.680 --> 00:33:16.800
[Amit Varma]: responding to the demand from industry that, you know, give us these sort of people who do these

00:33:16.800 --> 00:33:21.120
[Amit Varma]: sort of things. And you've also you know, in the past, you were one of the early members of

00:33:21.120 --> 00:33:26.320
[Amit Varma]: the Center for Civil Society in Delhi in the late 1990s. And you're fairly familiar with

00:33:26.880 --> 00:33:30.880
[Amit Varma]: education also. And would you say that's a big part of the puzzle?

00:33:30.880 --> 00:33:37.200
[Guest]: That's definitely part of the puzzle. Agreed. Because most people that come out of even

00:33:37.200 --> 00:33:44.400
[Guest]: engineering colleges, you know, are not, you know, qualified to do basic tasks in an engineering firm.

00:33:45.200 --> 00:33:51.840
[Guest]: So that kind of mismatch between what our education says on paper and what skills are

00:33:51.840 --> 00:33:57.680
[Guest]: actually learned in education is true. We need to improve that. So that's one really big part

00:33:57.680 --> 00:34:03.280
[Guest]: of the problem. The other part of the problem is that we don't have an apprenticeship issue. So,

00:34:03.280 --> 00:34:09.840
[Guest]: you know, there are countries which have big apprenticeship programs where, you know, kids

00:34:09.840 --> 00:34:16.880
[Guest]: are apprenticed with, you know, somebody who's working in that area. And you spend one, two,

00:34:16.880 --> 00:34:21.120
[Guest]: three years as an apprentice, and then you learn that skill, and then you are able to do that on

00:34:21.120 --> 00:34:26.480
[Guest]: your own. So you are able, you then get to be much better skilled than just what an education

00:34:26.480 --> 00:34:31.280
[Amit Varma]: would give you. And other countries also respect dignity of labor. Correct. Which is, you know,

00:34:31.280 --> 00:34:36.080
[Amit Varma]: not the case here, as in these kids that Mohit speaks about, he's seen them grow up and for them

00:34:36.080 --> 00:34:40.960
[Amit Varma]: being a plumber or a watchman is below their dignity, they would rather do nothing at all.

00:34:41.760 --> 00:34:46.960
[Guest]: That's right. And I mean, I'll give you a personal example. My cousin's son is a plumber in

00:34:46.960 --> 00:34:52.480
[Guest]: Australia, and he's perfectly happy with it. It's it's something that he does, you know, out of great

00:34:52.480 --> 00:34:59.840
[Guest]: joy, you know, doing that. It's if you were to ask if he was living in India, would he be happy

00:34:59.840 --> 00:35:05.680
[Guest]: doing it being a plumber? Maybe not, because there isn't even that social kind of acceptance

00:35:05.680 --> 00:35:10.400
[Amit Varma]: of certain trades. Maybe I'm just thinking aloud, and maybe caste also has something to do with it.

00:35:10.400 --> 00:35:14.160
[Amit Varma]: Because those kind of jobs, menial jobs are done by the lower caste, and therefore that social

00:35:14.160 --> 00:35:21.440
[Guest]: angle gets into it. That's also possible. I was also looking at another aspect of this,

00:35:21.440 --> 00:35:28.160
[Guest]: which is vulnerability. When we're looking at jobs, we're also looking at wages. Now,

00:35:28.160 --> 00:35:35.680
[Guest]: one stat that really hit me recently was 80% of casual workers and 30% of regular salaried workers

00:35:36.400 --> 00:35:41.920
[Guest]: earn less than what is the minimum wage in this country, which is approximately 66 rupees on

00:35:41.920 --> 00:35:46.240
[Guest]: average, you know, depending on where you are, minimum wage is a local subject, so different

00:35:46.240 --> 00:35:52.000
[Guest]: areas have different minimum wages. 66 rupees for what unit? Per day. Per day. Per day, luckily.

00:35:52.000 --> 00:35:58.880
[Guest]: And around about 78% of people in this country are vulnerable in the sense that they're either

00:35:58.880 --> 00:36:04.960
[Guest]: self-employed or what we call unemployed, in which case they are not employed by somebody else.

00:36:05.520 --> 00:36:11.360
[Guest]: They are responsible for, you know, raising their own salaries or their own income.

00:36:11.360 --> 00:36:16.480
[Guest]: Prime Minister once talked about, you know, pakoda sellers being, you know, a viable job.

00:36:16.480 --> 00:36:24.160
[Guest]: And it really isn't because what people are looking for is security and stability. And what

00:36:24.160 --> 00:36:28.960
[Guest]: what we find instead is exactly the opposite, a large amount of vulnerability in jobs.

00:36:29.760 --> 00:36:33.040
[Guest]: So much so that, you know, Manish Sabharwal of Team Lease has talked about

00:36:33.760 --> 00:36:39.200
[Guest]: this not being a jobs problem in the country, but a wages problem and a vulnerability problem

00:36:39.200 --> 00:36:45.360
[Guest]: where it's important that when we're talking about jobs, we're talking about the jobs of

00:36:45.360 --> 00:36:50.480
[Guest]: people who are unemployed. And it's important that when we're talking about a job, we should

00:36:50.480 --> 00:36:57.280
[Guest]: talk about something that gives a certain level of stability to the worker. And that is missing today.

00:36:57.280 --> 00:37:01.280
[Amit Varma]: So which basically comes down to saying that, you know, you might say that on paper,

00:37:01.280 --> 00:37:06.720
[Amit Varma]: there are X number of jobs, but if a significant percentage of them don't have a security and

00:37:06.720 --> 00:37:12.320
[Amit Varma]: stability and B don't have high enough wages to really be meaningful in any sense of investing

00:37:12.320 --> 00:37:18.320
[Guest]: it, they very often are not. So that level of vulnerability is something that we need to look at.

00:37:18.960 --> 00:37:22.800
[Guest]: Another figure that I was talking about, what I was thinking of talking about when we're talking

00:37:22.800 --> 00:37:28.000
[Guest]: about productivity earlier, is employment elasticity. So this might be a slightly wonky

00:37:28.000 --> 00:37:33.520
[Guest]: economics term to discuss. You've already lost me. Carry on, I'm sorry. Tell us what it is.

00:37:34.720 --> 00:37:39.200
[Guest]: One thing that we've talked about a lot of times is that if the economy grows, if GDP grows,

00:37:39.200 --> 00:37:44.400
[Guest]: employment grows along with it. So one way to make sure that we have jobs is to simply let

00:37:44.400 --> 00:37:50.160
[Guest]: the economy grow. But that may or may not be true. So one of the things we look at is what's called

00:37:50.160 --> 00:37:54.960
[Guest]: the employment elasticity of income, which is a correlation of employment with GDP. Correct. So

00:37:54.960 --> 00:38:02.960
[Guest]: this percentage of change in employment associated with a one percentage point change in GDP growth.

00:38:02.960 --> 00:38:08.800
[Guest]: So it's the ability of an economy to generate employment opportunities for its population,

00:38:08.800 --> 00:38:16.160
[Guest]: as the economy grows. So if your elasticity is one, it means that for every point that GDP grows,

00:38:16.160 --> 00:38:22.000
[Guest]: you have a one percentage point growth in jobs as well, which is ideal. If it's zero,

00:38:22.000 --> 00:38:26.080
[Guest]: it means that jobs don't grow at all. Productivity grows, but jobs don't.

00:38:26.080 --> 00:38:33.040
[Guest]: So it simply means that the economy grows, but jobs don't grow at all. And the worst part is if

00:38:33.040 --> 00:38:38.880
[Guest]: it's negative, which means that the economy grows, but jobs actually shrink. It means that, you know,

00:38:38.880 --> 00:38:45.600
[Guest]: maybe you're getting more capital intensive jobs. So between 99 and 2000 to 2004 and five,

00:38:45.600 --> 00:38:52.960
[Guest]: our employment elasticity was around about 0.5, 0.5, which meant that for every percentage that

00:38:52.960 --> 00:39:00.720
[Guest]: the economy grew, we got 0.5% growth in jobs. So like if the economy grew 7%, you would have a 3.5%

00:39:00.720 --> 00:39:09.840
[Guest]: growth in jobs. Correct. The next five years, from 2004, five to 2009, 10, we saw an employment

00:39:09.840 --> 00:39:17.680
[Guest]: elasticity of 0.01, which meant basically as the economy grew, we got hardly any jobs. So virtually

00:39:17.680 --> 00:39:26.480
[Guest]: it was close to zero. In the last, from 2009, 10 to 2011, 12, the last years we had the figures for

00:39:26.480 --> 00:39:33.040
[Guest]: this was like 0.18. It's a worrying figure because what it tells us is that the economy will still

00:39:33.040 --> 00:39:37.920
[Guest]: grow, but jobs don't grow along with the economy, which is one thing that we would like to see.

00:39:37.920 --> 00:39:43.520
[Amit Varma]: And it might indicate that the economy is growing in the more highly skilled sectors rather than.

00:39:43.520 --> 00:39:48.400
[Guest]: Correct. So part of it could be good when we're looking at say agriculture, we see that the

00:39:48.400 --> 00:39:56.240
[Guest]: agricultural employment elasticity is negative. It's minus 0.041, which means as the economy grows,

00:39:56.240 --> 00:40:03.040
[Guest]: agricultural sector loses jobs. What we would like to see, and some of it is heartening that

00:40:03.040 --> 00:40:07.840
[Guest]: we would like to see a corresponding growth in other sectors. So in manufacturing, we do see

00:40:07.840 --> 00:40:13.680
[Guest]: some amount of growth, we see an employment elasticity of 0.33. But in a sector like

00:40:13.680 --> 00:40:19.520
[Guest]: construction, we see an employment elasticity of one. So as the economy grows, construction adds

00:40:19.520 --> 00:40:24.800
[Guest]: the same number of jobs in a sense in its sector as the economy grows. And because farming can't

00:40:24.800 --> 00:40:28.720
[Amit Varma]: sustain so many workers, they move to manufacturing, they move especially to construction,

00:40:28.720 --> 00:40:33.440
[Amit Varma]: and they move into urban areas where there are more opportunities for them, which is a shift in

00:40:33.440 --> 00:40:37.840
[Guest]: the right direction, which is a shift that we should be seeing. We should be seeing a higher

00:40:38.400 --> 00:40:43.120
[Guest]: employment elasticity in manufacturing, because that's one sector that we see when people move

00:40:43.120 --> 00:40:47.760
[Guest]: out of agriculture, we see people largely moving into manufacturing. In India, we've seen a lot of

00:40:47.760 --> 00:40:55.040
[Guest]: people moving straight to services. So we see, for example, the guy who is unemployed in agriculture

00:40:55.040 --> 00:40:59.440
[Guest]: in the rural areas comes to the urban areas and most probably works as a swiggy driver.

00:40:59.440 --> 00:41:05.280
[Amit Varma]: Right, which is also great. I mean, now here's my next question to you. I mean, you know, this is

00:41:05.280 --> 00:41:11.840
[Amit Varma]: clearly not something that any one party can be blamed for per se. Our whole system of governance

00:41:11.840 --> 00:41:18.320
[Amit Varma]: is like this has been like this for 71 plus years. And I think we have broadly agreed that a lot of

00:41:18.320 --> 00:41:25.040
[Amit Varma]: this has been caused by the draconian nature of the state. But having said all of that, what can

00:41:25.040 --> 00:41:29.360
[Amit Varma]: the state now do to mitigate this, for example, all the recent agitations which have happened,

00:41:29.360 --> 00:41:36.160
[Amit Varma]: Jats, Marathas, Partidas, etc, are all a demand to the state to be the solution to this and that

00:41:36.160 --> 00:41:41.600
[Amit Varma]: in no specific cases give us reservations. But otherwise, broadly, people sort of tend to look

00:41:41.600 --> 00:41:45.440
[Amit Varma]: at the Narendra Modi government and say that, hey, you know, okay, the previous guys might have done

00:41:45.440 --> 00:41:50.960
[Amit Varma]: whatever, you create the jobs, can they create the jobs? To what extent can they solve this problem?

00:41:50.960 --> 00:41:55.840
[Guest]: So let me talk about some of the government schemes that are there and see how those work out.

00:41:56.400 --> 00:42:02.560
[Guest]: So the flagship scheme that was started out by the UPA government before and has been continued by

00:42:02.560 --> 00:42:09.280
[Guest]: the Modi government is the National Rural Employment Guarantee Scheme, which is called NREGA

00:42:09.280 --> 00:42:15.840
[Guest]: or M Mahatma Gandhi National Rural Employment Guarantee Scheme. And one of the things we found

00:42:15.840 --> 00:42:21.840
[Guest]: out is that it does improve food security. So people there, you know, who enroll under it,

00:42:22.480 --> 00:42:28.400
[Guest]: do have a better chance of having better livelihood to some extent. However, what it has

00:42:28.400 --> 00:42:34.480
[Guest]: also done is it has killed the development of micro enterprises in villages. So small businesses,

00:42:34.480 --> 00:42:40.560
[Guest]: small enterprises in villages have largely been killed because of the income that it provides

00:42:40.560 --> 00:42:46.720
[Guest]: and farmers out there. The other thing that studies have found in NREGA is that it doesn't

00:42:46.720 --> 00:42:53.280
[Guest]: effectively target people. So only approximately 26% of those, you know, applying for jobs and

00:42:53.280 --> 00:42:58.560
[Guest]: getting jobs in that are below the poverty line. Ideally, that figure should have been 100%. But

00:42:58.560 --> 00:43:04.640
[Guest]: only 26% below poverty line are actually those who are getting benefit from this scheme.

00:43:05.520 --> 00:43:10.960
[Guest]: Another scheme that the Prime Minister has talked about is being the Mudra scheme, you know, the

00:43:10.960 --> 00:43:18.000
[Guest]: scheme that where he's looking at self-employment and trying to improve entrepreneurship. The Mudra

00:43:18.000 --> 00:43:23.600
[Guest]: scheme gives loans to, you know, micro entrepreneurs. And there are three kinds of

00:43:23.600 --> 00:43:29.440
[Guest]: loans given. There's Shishu loan, which is up to 50,000 rupees, the Kishore loan, which is 50,000

00:43:29.440 --> 00:43:37.440
[Guest]: rupees to 5 lakhs, and the Tarun, which is 5 lakhs to around about 1 million, so around about 10

00:43:37.440 --> 00:43:45.360
[Guest]: lakhs. And what we find out that out of the 32.7 million loans that have been given out,

00:43:46.000 --> 00:43:51.680
[Guest]: rupees and loans that have been given out, the vast majority, 30.3 are Shishu loans. So these

00:43:51.680 --> 00:43:58.320
[Guest]: are loans that are 50,000 rupees or less. And, you know, researchers said that this is not really

00:43:58.320 --> 00:44:07.280
[Guest]: enough to create jobs. There have been reports of 55 million new jobs being created. But it's

00:44:07.280 --> 00:44:12.560
[Guest]: highly unlikely that these loans have been given out to people who were previously unemployed.

00:44:12.560 --> 00:44:16.320
[Guest]: So these have been given out to people who were previously employed in something else. So these

00:44:16.320 --> 00:44:22.640
[Guest]: 55 million jobs that have been talked about in the Mudra scheme, as most probably no new net jobs

00:44:22.640 --> 00:44:27.040
[Guest]: have been created. We've just seen a shift in jobs from one area to another.

00:44:28.080 --> 00:44:32.800
[Amit Varma]: And also, you don't see the opportunity cost of all this, like if the money was spent elsewhere,

00:44:32.800 --> 00:44:38.480
[Amit Varma]: it would have maybe created jobs there and that not happening has, you know, those are the unseen

00:44:38.480 --> 00:44:41.680
[Guest]: effects. Correct. So if money was spent in, for example, in infrastructure, we might have seen a

00:44:41.680 --> 00:44:48.240
[Guest]: much larger effect in it. There are other, you know, PM, EGP and the Pradhan Mantri Rozgar

00:44:48.240 --> 00:44:54.080
[Guest]: Protsahan Yojana and the Gram Sadak Yojana and there are a lot of schemes that come out. But

00:44:54.080 --> 00:44:59.840
[Guest]: my main issue with a lot of these schemes is that one assumes that the government is the one that

00:44:59.840 --> 00:45:06.880
[Guest]: should come out with the solutions. But what we've seen is a few things that we've been talking

00:45:06.880 --> 00:45:12.960
[Guest]: about internally about what could the ideal solutions be to these issues. The first would

00:45:12.960 --> 00:45:19.040
[Guest]: be a focus on large enterprises, not small and micro enterprises. We need to see a scale up in

00:45:19.040 --> 00:45:26.880
[Guest]: industry because that's where most jobs get created. So that's where we see a much greater

00:45:26.880 --> 00:45:34.160
[Guest]: labor participation, where we see a much greater need for a labor force. And currently what's

00:45:34.160 --> 00:45:39.440
[Guest]: happening is we are focusing on the small and micro and the unorganized sector, therefore,

00:45:40.000 --> 00:45:46.640
[Guest]: while the challenge is to bolster our organized sector, have more jobs come in the organized

00:45:46.640 --> 00:45:51.920
[Guest]: sector and the formal sector. And that will happen only when we see industry scaling up and we see

00:45:52.560 --> 00:45:57.360
[Amit Varma]: larger and larger companies. And you'd say that the government should enable that by getting out

00:45:57.360 --> 00:46:02.000
[Guest]: of the way. Correct. That's right. Other thing, of course, that the government should do is reform

00:46:02.000 --> 00:46:11.600
[Guest]: labor laws. This is an issue perhaps for another podcast or series of podcasts on the problem that

00:46:11.600 --> 00:46:17.200
[Guest]: we're having in labor laws. But one of the things we see, why we see that even our employment

00:46:17.200 --> 00:46:24.080
[Guest]: necessity is low is because when companies do scale up, they'd rather invest in capital than

00:46:24.080 --> 00:46:30.160
[Guest]: take the trouble of hiring more labor because of all the issues that we have with labor laws in

00:46:30.160 --> 00:46:36.080
[Guest]: the country. So reforming labor laws is a big thing the government can do. And what reforming

00:46:36.080 --> 00:46:40.480
[Amit Varma]: labor laws would also do is like your first point was about focus on large industry focus on

00:46:41.280 --> 00:46:47.120
[Amit Varma]: getting companies in the formal sector to scale. But since most of this country's business is

00:46:47.120 --> 00:46:52.480
[Amit Varma]: conducted in the informal sector, what reforming labor laws completely would also do is it would

00:46:52.480 --> 00:46:56.480
[Amit Varma]: remove the disincentives for a lot of those companies to come into the formal sector.

00:46:56.480 --> 00:47:00.560
[Amit Varma]: Correct. Because a lot of the compliance issues they face are because of these mad labor laws.

00:47:00.560 --> 00:47:03.600
[Amit Varma]: Correct. That if you have more than 20 people, you have to do this, you have to do that,

00:47:03.600 --> 00:47:07.520
[Amit Varma]: you have to do this. So typically, you just can't scale, you can't comply. And therefore,

00:47:07.520 --> 00:47:11.920
[Amit Varma]: if you reform them and make them sensible, like in most of the world, then, you know,

00:47:11.920 --> 00:47:18.080
[Amit Varma]: more of the informal sector comes into the formal sector in a natural, organic way with the right

00:47:18.080 --> 00:47:23.520
[Amit Varma]: incentives rather than sort of be coerced into it and inevitably shut down. That's right.

00:47:23.520 --> 00:47:29.280
[Guest]: The third thing that we're looking for is to create an environment for investment in new cities,

00:47:29.280 --> 00:47:35.440
[Guest]: because largely what we're seeing is we're seeing greater employment in urban areas compared to

00:47:35.440 --> 00:47:40.960
[Guest]: rural areas. We want to see that as well, because we want to see people moving out of agriculture

00:47:40.960 --> 00:47:46.240
[Guest]: and the rural areas into more urban areas. And one way of that happening is infrastructure

00:47:46.240 --> 00:47:52.160
[Guest]: development, the establishment of new cities. The prime minister had once talked about creating

00:47:52.160 --> 00:47:59.600
[Guest]: 100 new cities. I think we most probably had one most probably coming up Amravati in the new state

00:47:59.600 --> 00:48:04.800
[Guest]: in Andhra Pradesh. So, but is it the government job to create new cities? I don't think it's the

00:48:04.800 --> 00:48:09.520
[Guest]: government job to create new cities. It's the government's job to create incentives, right,

00:48:09.520 --> 00:48:15.120
[Guest]: or basically stay out of the way so that new urban centers can come up. Right. And it's these

00:48:15.120 --> 00:48:20.560
[Guest]: new urban centers that will create more jobs, which will create better infrastructure, just

00:48:20.560 --> 00:48:26.400
[Guest]: building new cities itself will create more jobs on a temporary basis. But beyond that, we have

00:48:27.600 --> 00:48:34.480
[Guest]: a lot of potential in areas of health care, in areas of education, things that we need to improve

00:48:34.480 --> 00:48:39.440
[Guest]: for our own country, and areas that, you know, for higher education that we can build for the rest of

00:48:39.440 --> 00:48:47.200
[Guest]: the world as well. So these are areas that are potential solutions for us, where we can absorb

00:48:47.200 --> 00:48:54.000
[Guest]: the 20 million that each year that is going to come out for the next few years for us. So we need

00:48:54.000 --> 00:49:01.680
[Guest]: to have a plan that can absorb that many new entrants to the labor force every year. So it's

00:49:01.680 --> 00:49:09.120
[Guest]: not that we have 20 million jobs as one final figure. It's 20 million jobs every year that need

00:49:09.120 --> 00:49:14.800
[Amit Varma]: to be created. And even not just the 20 million jobs created for the new entrance into the workforce,

00:49:14.800 --> 00:49:19.040
[Amit Varma]: but also taking into account that there's a lot of this guy's unemployment, that a lot of people

00:49:19.040 --> 00:49:23.360
[Amit Varma]: are underemployed, that they don't have, for example, that there's that there's so much labor

00:49:23.360 --> 00:49:28.560
[Amit Varma]: vulnerability where you're selling pakoras and that's not really a real job. It's not even you

00:49:28.560 --> 00:49:33.200
[Amit Varma]: can't even call that guy an entrepreneur because he's not building a business. He's just surviving

00:49:33.200 --> 00:49:39.920
[Amit Varma]: on a day to day basis. And you know, tell me if you agree, but I think the fundamental problem of

00:49:39.920 --> 00:49:45.360
[Amit Varma]: why we are in this mess is a mindset problem we've had for 71 years. And that's a mindset problem

00:49:45.360 --> 00:49:51.920
[Amit Varma]: of command and control, that an economy can be planned from above. And that essentially,

00:49:52.640 --> 00:49:56.640
[Amit Varma]: you know, it's that whole thing about the citizens of a country being subjects to the rulers and the

00:49:56.640 --> 00:50:01.200
[Amit Varma]: rulers will set the rules and decide what happens and give the requisite permissions for everything

00:50:01.200 --> 00:50:07.520
[Amit Varma]: and keep every everyone on tight leash. And what that has done is that that that didn't allow a

00:50:07.520 --> 00:50:12.640
[Amit Varma]: manufacturing revolution to happen in India when it should have because our greatest strength was

00:50:13.520 --> 00:50:20.160
[Amit Varma]: our labor force in China stole the marsh there. And despite the limited liberalization of 91,

00:50:20.160 --> 00:50:24.800
[Amit Varma]: and I always use the word limited with it because it really it was it was very limited

00:50:26.160 --> 00:50:29.200
[Amit Varma]: and not a true liberalization and despite that that mindset still

00:50:29.760 --> 00:50:33.440
[Amit Varma]: persists whether it was in the previous UPA government or whether it is with

00:50:33.440 --> 00:50:38.480
[Amit Varma]: Narendra Modi that okay, government will do this, we'll build all these cities, we'll do this,

00:50:38.480 --> 00:50:43.440
[Amit Varma]: we'll skill people will and that's completely the wrong mindset, the right mindset, which these

00:50:43.440 --> 00:50:47.600
[Amit Varma]: people don't have, because they don't understand spontaneous orders and how economies and cities

00:50:47.600 --> 00:50:55.440
[Amit Varma]: work in a positive some way is that you just allow the entrepreneurial energy of people to express

00:50:55.440 --> 00:51:02.400
[Amit Varma]: itself, allow it fully. And when that happens, all this will take care of itself, growth will happen,

00:51:02.400 --> 00:51:07.920
[Amit Varma]: jobs will come. And I think most people don't understand except people who run businesses

00:51:07.920 --> 00:51:12.480
[Amit Varma]: themselves, the extent to which we are still tied up in chains.

00:51:13.200 --> 00:51:19.200
[Guest]: True. That's quite true. So it's not the question of just creating lakhs and lakhs of entrepreneurs

00:51:19.200 --> 00:51:24.720
[Guest]: either. It's, you know, it's just perhaps creating a few 1000 entrepreneurs, who would then be able

00:51:24.720 --> 00:51:31.840
[Guest]: to employ hundreds of 1000s of people themselves, right. So when we talk because there's a lot of

00:51:31.840 --> 00:51:38.400
[Guest]: talk about, you know, how entrepreneurship would be the next revolution. And one must be careful

00:51:38.400 --> 00:51:41.120
[Guest]: that you know, when you're talking about entrepreneurship, we're not talking about

00:51:41.120 --> 00:51:47.280
[Guest]: the pakodawala as an entrepreneur, right? We are talking about an entrepreneur who actually employs

00:51:47.840 --> 00:51:55.360
[Guest]: a few 1000 people, at least himself or herself. Right. So, you know, I know that 20 million jobs

00:51:55.360 --> 00:51:59.840
[Amit Varma]: project that you are on is still sort of at an early stage is still kind of gathering all of

00:51:59.840 --> 00:52:05.920
[Amit Varma]: the data and you don't want to commit to sort of talking about solutions this early and at

00:52:05.920 --> 00:52:10.160
[Amit Varma]: a later point when you're ready, we'll do a separate episode on that once you have better,

00:52:11.280 --> 00:52:17.760
[Amit Varma]: more clarity on what specific policy measures and so on you'd like to suggest. But just looking at

00:52:17.760 --> 00:52:21.360
[Amit Varma]: sort of the scenario of jobs in India, and it really looks bleak to me because you have all

00:52:21.360 --> 00:52:26.320
[Amit Varma]: these young men coming out into the workforce, no jobs, all the relevant social problems that

00:52:26.320 --> 00:52:30.720
[Amit Varma]: we discussed and it looks bleak to me, I know you're more hopeful about it. So my question to

00:52:30.720 --> 00:52:37.920
[Amit Varma]: you is, what makes you despair? And what makes you hopeful about the medium term, let's say the next

00:52:37.920 --> 00:52:46.320
[Guest]: 10 years of India, keeping our youth in mind. So what makes me hopeful is that we do have,

00:52:47.760 --> 00:52:53.920
[Guest]: you know, youth that are coming out and that are taking, you know, a lot of things and taking their

00:52:53.920 --> 00:52:59.360
[Guest]: own future in their own hands. In a sense, we talked about Snigdha Poonam's book in Dreamers,

00:52:59.360 --> 00:53:04.320
[Guest]: when you talk about the first few chapters of the book where you have the guy who's teaching,

00:53:04.320 --> 00:53:10.000
[Guest]: taking English classes, or the one who's setting up a clickbait factory. So these are young people

00:53:10.000 --> 00:53:14.720
